I decide the best way to get my feet wet in some of the newer technologies and re-hone my coding skills would to create a Blog (from scratch) about the Glad2Cook creation process. 
{BR}{BR}
Since the purpose of this Blog (odd really… I not even a big fan of Blogs) is to get a little head start in modern development techniques before diving in to G2C, I am going to force myself to use all kinds of fancy stuff: XML, RSS, Validation Controls, DataGrids, DataLists, DataViews, more Visual Studio stuff, more involved CSS, etc, etc). 
{BR}{BR}
I have owned {a href="http://jasonbutler.com"}jasonbutler.com{/a} for awhile, and since I have never really used it, what better time to put it to work than now.

I actually got {a href="http://www.webpronews.com/webdevelopment/webapplications/wpn-27-20050720SyndicatingYourWebSitesContentwithRSSandASPNET.html
"}this C# version{/a} of dynamically creating a RSS services from code to work - I could not get a VB version to work at first.
{BR}{BR}
But I eventually did.
{BR}{BR}
Turns out I accidentally took out the code for displaying the finished data when I (temporarily) took out the caching code. I also removed the first line of the html code - the line that tells the server that it has a corresponding vb code file.

I put links to my static html header and footer includes files (named {a href="http://jasonbutler.com/G2CBlog/heading.txt"}heading.txt{/a} and {a href="http://jasonbutler.com/G2CBlog/footer.txt"}footer.txt{/a} - may open as text or as html, depending on your browser) into the html of Blog.aspx. Don’t know if this is the “proper” way to include fancy design stuff around the REAL code, but it works (after making sure your page is set to FlowLayout that is).
{BR}{BR}
{IMG SRC="http://jasonbutler.com/G2CBlog/header.jpg" ALT="Headers and Footers" BORDER="0"}

Trying to use CSS with my Blog application. Turns out VS starts each web project with a Style.css file (who knew). You still have to put the line &lt;LINK REL="stylesheet" TYPE="text/css" HREF="styles.css"&gt; right above the &lt;HEAD&gt; line in the html. 
{BR}{BR}
I simply pasted my CSS code to the bottom of the Style.css – it looks like .NET use the later code when duplicates are around (i.e. my BODY color is used instead of the default one). Also CSS tags in the design environment works as expected – type in a tag name and that’s what it will use (i.e. for a label I typed in errmsg (a CSS tag I defined), and the text instantly turned red).

Got web address and formatting working in the XML file. Could not find a lot of info on putting greater than and less than symbols “{” and “}” directly into the XML file. Because obviously, the XML file treats those symbols as part of the data tags. However using a simple replace command I switch &#123; &#125; symbols to { } for actual page display. Now I just have to put the reverse replace command into the create Blog entry page (which I need to create). 
{BR}{BR}
PS: It was tricky getting those curly brackets to display above.

Working on Blog Entry page. Already learned a few things to do when adding a page to the project. Add the following to each new page:
{BR}{BR}
Below &lt;BODY&gt;
{BR}
&lt;!--#include file="heading.txt"--&gt;
{BR}
Above &lt;/BODY&gt;
{BR}
&lt;!--#include file="footer.txt"--&gt;
{BR}{BR}
Above &lt;/HEAD&gt;
{BR}
&lt;LINK REL="stylesheet" TYPE="text/css" HREF="styles.css"&gt;
{BR}
&lt;LINK REL="Shortcut Icon" href="jason.ico"&gt;
{BR}{BR}
Set the pageLayout to FlowLayout (any object added before this is changed will have fixed positions, so delete them and re-add ‘em).

Finaly figured out how to easily read the first record in a DataView populated by an XML file (got it round about from my old ASP.NET Unleashed book). The magic code after the sort is: 
{BR}{BR}
txtNumber.Text = DvwBlog(0).Row("NUMBER") + 1

To actual use your XML schema in your DataSet (make a field numeric) you must point to the schema file, and it must come BEFORE the regular XML file.
{BR}{BR}
DstBlog.ReadXmlSchema(Server.MapPath("blog.xsd"))
{BR}
DstBlog.ReadXml(Server.MapPath("blog.xml"))

Added users ASPNET and IUSRNOTEBOOK to the Administrators Group. Made the Blog folder shared and added Read access to the allowed actives in IIS. 
{BR}{BR}
And I’m still having problems with my app writing to the XML file!

I don’t know how many hundreds of times I have told users to try rebooting their computers first when they run in to problems. 
{BR}{BR}
Well after rebooting, my Blog app is able to write to the XML file fine. Don’t know which of the three changes I made where necessary. 
{BR}{BR}
I’ll back them out (or change to lower levels) to find out what is the minimum changes I can get by with.

Now the date field is not sorting properly. Changed the XML schema to dateTime, but now reading and writing to the XML won’t work. 
{BR}{BR}
Finally figure out the secret to XML conversion (XML has to store the date funky).
{BR}{BR}
Here's some examples:
{BR}
Test.Text = XmlConvert.ToDateTime("2006-05-09T15:24:51.0000000-04:00")
{BR}
Test.Text = XmlConvert.ToString(CDate("5/9/2006 3:24:51 PM"))

Had to set the ValidateRequest="false" in the &lt;%@ Page section of the HTML, to get the below strings to upload correctly (ASP.NET thinks they’re potential virus attacks).
{BR}{BR}
&lt;a href="http://www.yahoo.com"&gt;Y!&lt;/a&gt;

I found out it is VERY importing formatting/spacing wise to put one space in front of the ErrorMessage in Validator controls.
{BR}{BR}
Not only does it help space error messages one space from the controls, but more importantly it doesn’t screw up your text wrapping (especially with carefully created tables).

When formatting for different browsers (non IE), it is important to let .NET know which browsers to use high level code for. The key is to include the correct &lt;browserCaps&gt; in the web.config file of the project (inside of the &lt;system.web&gt; tag). I used the ones from: 
{BR}{BR}
{a href="http://slingfive.com/pages/code/browserCaps/"}http://slingfive.com/pages/code/browserCaps/{/a}
{BR}{BR}
And they worked like a charm.

Had problem’s setting the browser page title on the Blog Entry screen. Turn out all I had to do was set my page variable to Protected (or public) and it works perfect. 
{BR}{BR}
(This probably would have help display via the Find command).

I followed the {a href="http://kb.discountasp.net/article.aspx?id=10002"}
instructions{/a} for deploying a Visual Studio .NET web project from my local computer to DiscountASP.Net servers.
{BR}{BR}
Would not copy file, something about couldn’t find file or file lock out? It never even asked me for a password. So I Did the Build Solution and Build Blog commands to Release (instead of my usual Debug). Then did the Copy Project and it worked like a charm. Had to add a default.htm page for a redirect however – but everything at jasonbutler.com now looks good.

I added a quick (and obviously needed) Edit feature to my Blog entry page. 
{BR}{BR}
Surprisingly it was easy to do and it works quite well.

Ok so I’ve been away for awhile... if you want to read the Blog of an {a href="http://joelonsoftware.com/"}ambitious{/a} {a href="http://www.ericsink.com/"}developer {/a}
 you’ll need to go elsewhere.
{BR}{BR}
I decide to go ahead and add the RSS feed I was {a href=" http://jasonbutler.com/G2CBlog/BlogEntry.aspx?Entry=21"}toying with earlier{/a}, to my Blog.
{BR}{BR}
I already had the basic code working, I just had to add in the code to read to 10 most recent Blog entries from the XML file (a DataView did the trick). A little fine tuning here and there – add an {a href="http://feedicons.com/"}icon{/a} to the link (see it, over to the left, just below my cool little site description). And my humble {a href=" http://jasonbutler.com/G2CBlog/RSSFeed.aspx"}RSS feed{/a} works nice and dandy.

1) In VS.NET, rebuilt the Solution and the Project (Blog) in Release mode.
{BR}{BR}
2) Next click Copy Project from the Project menu.
{BR}{BR}
3) {B}Destination project folder{/B} should be the web address (http://jasonbutler.com). The {B}Web access method{/B} should be Front Page, the {B}Copy{/B} should be Only files needed to run this application.
{BR}{BR}
4) {B}User name{/B} should be the web hosting user name (may have to change from default). The {B}Password{/B} should be the web hosting password.
{BR}{BR}
Be careful which files get uploaded - it could copy over newer live files. Also keep in mind that files not specifically in the project will not be copied (you can always FTP basic files).

A couple of weeks ago the wife decided she needed a laptop for her work so I done the only thing a loving husband could do – I gave here my old laptop and went out to buy myself a new PC.
{BR}{BR}
I know a lot of development gurus like to buy high end laptops – but I have honestly never found a big enough benefit to buying a $2000 laptop over a $700 one. 
{BR}{BR}
So with that in mind (and the Sunday paper in hand) I quickly decide on the Toshiba Satellite A105-S4074. This laptop is selling all over the web for $900 to $1000, but for some reason it is going for $700 (after rebates) at {a href=" http://www.compusa.com/products/product_info.asp?product_code=339936
"}CompUSA{/a} 
{BR}{BR} 
Surprisingly they had plenty in stock when I showed up – but they just could not let me have the computer with out an all out effort to sell me an extended warranty. They lowered the price from $200 to $150. The salesman said he has never sold a laptop with out something breaking on it in the first 6 months (why are they selling such crap?). He tried to get me to sign something saying I did NOT want the warranty (no I didn’t sign). After several minutes of this and my absolute reassurance that this was not the sell to be pushing the warranty on (I wouldn’t want these guys working on computer for free) he finally sold me the laptop and let me go on my way.
{BR}{BR}
After literally two weeks of completely reconfiguring my laptop to exacting specifications (it had 71 processes running at idle out of the box! –
{a href="http://www.processlibrary.com/"}processlibrary.com{/a} seems to be the best website for figuring all this voodoo out) I am now up and running with a very serviceable laptop.
{BR}{BR}
…
{BR}{BR}
1) Yes I made a nicely little image (4 DVDs) of my laptop after setting everything up ever so carefully – so whenever I push my poor computer to the point of being frozen in terror, I can simply pop in a few DVDs and be back in business.
{BR}{BR}
2) Yes I kept MCE on the laptop. This was not my first choice, but after gutting out all the useless stuff (I really don’t need two inch people dancing around on my desktop) I got the Media stuff down to a manageable level. That and I don’t have an extra copy of XP Pro lying around – and it looks like MS has gone crazy with activation and verification (I even got caught in the infamous {a href="http://pressf1.pcworld.co.nz/showthread.php?t=69810"}Windows activation loop{/a}).
{BR}{BR}
3) Copying my VS.NET projects was relatively easy – just follow {a href="http://www.codeproject.com/aspnet/VSNETcopyproject.asp"}the steps{/a}.

