I’m back working on the G2C and my first thought, is there any kind of unofficial standard among the major web applications that G2C could benefit from?
{BR}{BR}
I looked at Amazon (shopping and wish list), eBay, Netflix (searching and queue), Wal-Mart and Target. Certainly not the fanciest web apps out there, but applications that get used often by non-geeks, and deal with long list. 
{BR}{BR}
Some interesting observations standout right away, like how much information and options these sites try to pack into each screen. It is also clear that there aren’t many unofficial standards on the web when it comes to the details. Example, Amazon’s wish list doesn’t save your changes when going to a new page before clicking Save, but eBay does. It’s clear that I’m just going to have to borrow the feature that I like best.
{BR}{BR}
{a href="http://jasonbutler.com/G2CBlog/Docs/MajorWebsiteInterfaces.doc"} Major Website Interfaces.doc {/a} 3MB (Word)

I’m back at the same problem {a href="http://jasonbutler.com/G2CBlog/BlogEntry.aspx?Entry=13"}
I was at last year{/a}, trying to choice which (MS) product to use for G2C.
{BR}{BR}
{B}VS.NET 2003{/B} - Have and know, but kind of old, uses ASP 1.1. I was planning to go this route, but it is starting to look pretty old
{BR}
{B}VS.NET 2005{/B} - Cost $700, but uses ASP 2.0 {a href="http://aspnet.4guysfromrolla.com/articles/120705-1.aspx"}(user accounts look interesting){/a}. I would probably go this route if I had the $$$.    
{BR}
{B}Visual Web Developer Express{/B} - FREE, uses ASP 2.0. Not really a professional dev tool, but it maybe the only way I can do ASP 2.0 for now.
{BR}
{B}VS.NET 2008{/B} - Not out till next year, ASP 3.5. Too new, definitely not looking to go this route.
{BR}{BR}
Not too mention {a href=" http://www.asp.net/ajax/"}ASP.NET AJAX{/a} is starting to look pretty cool (needs ASP 2.0).

Well through a bit of luck and skill I’ve acquired a full copy of VS.NET 2005.
{BR}{BR}
In a related coincidence I am working on implementing some AJAX enhanced ASP.NET 2.0 web pages at my place of employment. The server I’m using for this is primarily a file server and I’m just trying to discreetly piggy back on a few web apps. Everything was going pretty good until I deployed my first sample app from VS 05. No matter what page I tried to go to I received the following error:
{BR}{BR}
{font size="1" color="red"}
    System.Security.SecurityException: Requested registry access is not allowed. 
{/font}
{BR}{BR}
For several days I was convinced that is wasn’t directly a registry permission problem, because my sample apps certainly didn’t touch the registry and I turn off as much of the built in logging as possible.
{BR}{BR}	
After a few days of trial and error, and web research I decide to look closer at the registry on the server. By down loading a the handy register monitoring tool {a href="http://www.microsoft.com/technet/sysinternals/utilities/regmon.mspx"}RegMon{/a} I was able to find one registry lookup that was failing because of permissions, out of thousands of on going look ups (if you use this program be sure to use the filter to weed out programs that are obviously not the problem, like regmon.exe). 
{BR}{BR}
Well after tracking down this one registry entry I brought up the permissions, only Admin and System had any access. In most of the registry Users at least have read access, so I added Users with read access and BAM! Everything started working perfectly.

Instead of working on G2C, like I should be, I've been making learning games for my kids...
{BR}{BR}
{a href="http://beansgames.com/"}{IMG SRC="http://jasonbutler.com/BeansGames/bwg-screenshot.jpg" ALT="The Beans Word Game" BORDER="0"}{/a}
{BR}{BR}
The Beans Word Game is a simple little game that I made for my two daughters to help teach them spelling in a fun way.
{BR}{BR}
Playing the game is very simple. A word is said out loud while a picture of it is displayed. Next the word is spelled out on the screen as the letters are shown at the bottom. Then the letters disappear and the child is asked to spell the word. Encouragement and hints are given as the word is being typed.
{BR}{BR}
The Beans Word Game can be played by kids of any age by changing the game settings, or by making the spelling words easier or harder, but kids between four and eight will probably get the most out of it. 
{BR}{BR}
Download from the main website {a href="http://beansgames.com/"}BeansGames.com{/a}
{BR}{BR}
Or download from {a href="
http://www.download.com/Beans-Word-Game/3000-2102_4-10892816.html"}download.com{/a}

Like many other IT departments of large non-IT organizations, we still use some very old technology where I work - specifically QMF mainframe reports. We have been manually downloading these reports though a cumbersome mainframe emulator, and then converting them to Excel with a hit or miss processes using the fixed width Text to Columns tool. Then we would finally finish off the reports with column names, slightly prettier formatting and giving them useful file names. 
{BR}{BR}
Until I finally realized that this is just the type of busy work computers love to do. So I developed QMF2Excel to do just that.
{BR}{BR}
{a href="http://jasonbutler.com/QMF2Excel/"}{IMG SRC="http://jasonbutler.com/QMF2Excel/QMF2Excel-small.jpg" ALT="QMF2Excel" BORDER="0"}{/a}
{BR}{BR}
To find out more about QMF2Excel {a href="http://jasonbutler.com/QMF2Excel/"}click here{/a}.

I guess I really hadn’t thought about it, but I had no idea there were so many (in person) developer groups out there. Of course I am primarily interested in the Atlanta area, but there are groups setup all over the country. Many of them are organized grassroots style by fellow developers. Meetup.com is an excellent resource to find local groups – of course the old stand by of just googling for them works well too.
{BR}{BR}
These group are a fantastic way to keep up the latest technology and meet other local developers (and trade info on job leads). I love web cast of the latest tools and tips, but there is still something about seeing it done in person – and being able to ask questions on the spot.
{BR}{BR}
Most are free, or they charge a modest meeting fee to just cover expenses. Here in Atlanta a couple of groups meet at the local Microsoft building with food and drinks provided – and usually end with giveaway of quality books and software. It makes sense if you think about it – who helps out MS more than developers using and promoting their products!
{BR}{BR}
Here are a few groups that I have attended in the last couple months:
{BR}{BR}
{a href="http://www.atldotnet.org/default.aspx"}Altanta.net User Group{/a} meets one a month up in Alpharetta. I’ve been to a couple of meetings, a nice operation with good topics. 
{BR}{BR}
{a href="http://www.atlantamspros.com"}Atlanta Microsoft Professionals{/a} also meets once a month in Alpharetta at the MS building.
{BR}{BR}
{a href="http://www.meetup.com/atlantawebentrepreneurs"}Atlanta Web Entrepreneurs{/a} meet over by GA Tech, a mixed business, tech and college crowd.
{BR}{BR}
{a href="http://www.meetup.com/atlantawebdesign"}Atlanta Web Design Group{/a} a designer (artsy) crowd, they meet at the Portfolio Center in Atlanta.

This whole grocery list application idea has real potential… four years ago when I first thought it up! But now there are plenty of competitors out there that were obviously more ambitious than me.  
{BR}{BR}
However since I still need a project to (try) and keep my code skills some what up to date, I have decide to press on with Glad2Cook. 
{BR}{BR}
Now that I’m actually coding, my big problem is which direction to go in. I thought at first I wanted a full feature app – that was still pretty intuitive to use. But after adding more and more features you get to a point where, even if well designed, it’s just not as easy to use as it should be – especially on mobile devices.
{BR}{BR}
{I}Full Featured{/I}{BR}
{IMG SRC="http://jasonbutler.com/G2CBlog/images/g2c-shop.gif" BORDER="1"}
{BR}
{IMG SRC="http://jasonbutler.com/G2CBlog/images/g2c-list.gif" BORDER="1"}
{BR}{BR}
I know there’s already a lot out there supporting both sides of the debate, but it’s still tricky in practice. For example I’m going in the direct of easier and simpler right now. But I have basically scaled my grocery list application down to a very generic online list (application isn’t the right word) …thing. 
{BR}{BR}
{I}Easy / Simple{/I}{BR}
{IMG SRC="http://jasonbutler.com/G2CBlog/images/g2c-shop-simple.gif" BORDER="1"}
{BR}
{IMG SRC="http://jasonbutler.com/G2CBlog/images/g2c-list-simple.gif" BORDER="1"}
{BR}{BR}
I honestly don’t know which direct to take and I'm really leaning towards creating two complete different websites to serve both purposes.
